उर्वारू,<BR> f., Urva1ruka, n., ‘cucumber.’ The former 1) Av. vi. 14, 2. of these words denotes the plant, the latter 2) Rv. vii. 59, 12 = Av. xiv. 1, 17 = Maitra1yan2i1 Sam2hita1, i. 10, 4 = Taittiri1ya Sam2hita1, i. 8, 6, 2 = Va1jasaneyi Sam2hita1, iii. 60. the fruit, but both are very rare. The passages all seem to refer to the fact that the stem of the plant becomes loosened when the fruit is ripe. 3) Sa1yan2a on Av. vi. 14, 2. The fruit is also called Urva1ru in a Bra1hman2a. 4) Pan5cavim2s4a Bra1hman2a, ix. 2. 19. Cf. Zimmer, Altindisches Leben, 242.

