जर्तिल,<BR> ‘wild sesamum,’ is mentioned in the Taittiri1ya Sam2hita1 (v. 4, 3, 2) as an unsuitable sacrificial offering. In the S4atapatha Bra1hman2a (ix. 1, 1, 3) sesamum seeds are regarded as combining the qualities of cultivation (viz., edibility) with those of wild growth (because they are produced on unploughed land).

